@Tamarandom @wslyvh With help from @JeffEmmett , I think I figured it out.
The numbers for individual transactions are "off" (amt ≠ sqrt(cost)) when the same address gives votes to the same Proposal on separate occasions.

In the "data" tab, Row 2 and 4 are both votes from address 0xaa...8737 to Proposal 1. The total amount (22 + 294) is equal to the square root of the total cost (484 + 99732). The second amount has to be "off" to make the cumulative total work out.
The algorithm does the right thing by rounding down, else this could be exploited to squeeze out extra votes by splitting into multiple transactions.

When adding up total votes split across multiple proposals, this will always exceed the square root of voting power. This isn't an error; it's a design feature of QV that you have more votes if you vote for several things.
**TL;DR - all the numbers make sense.** Sorry if I confused anyone. ☺️

Talking with some folks about bringing quadratic voting to another chain. This was a concern raised. I’m sure this was considered when working out the framework. Can you please explain how this issue is addressed?
“I take it that Quadratic Voting would have to have some sort of identity-voting token pairing.  We can't allow some whale with 1,000 tokens to establish 10 wallets of 100 tokens each to get the same benefit as the minnow with 100 tokens.”

I think in context, that can be mitigated with how CSTK tokens work.
Afaik, they're non-transferable, so whales distributing them to multiple wallets that they own isn't a threat.
